# Corvid OS - AppArmor local overrides
# Security DNA component
#
# This directory holds SITE-LOCAL additions to the shipped AppArmor profiles.
# A stock profile in /etc/apparmor.d/<name> ends with a line like:
#
#     include if exists <local/<name>>
#
# ...so anything you put in a file here named EXACTLY after the profile is
# merged in WITHOUT editing (or fighting future package updates to) the
# upstream profile. Files in this directory that are not include-referenced by
# some profile are simply ignored by apparmor_parser - this README included.
#
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# WHY THIS EXISTS ON A PENTEST DISTRO
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# We enforce profiles (see hook 0200). Occasionally a confined system daemon a
# pentester actually needs - e.g. tcpdump reading from an odd path, or a tool
# that shells out - trips its profile. The right fix is a narrow local grant
# here, NOT flipping the whole profile to complain mode. Keep grants minimal
# and specific.
#
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# EXAMPLE (commented; copy into a file named for the target profile to use)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# File: /etc/apparmor.d/local/usr.bin.tcpdump
# -------------------------------------------------
#   # Let tcpdump write pcaps into the operator's capture dir.
#   owner /home/*/captures/** rw,
#   /home/*/captures/ rw,
# -------------------------------------------------
#
# After adding a local override on the live/installed system, reload it:
#   sudo apparmor_parser -r /etc/apparmor.d/usr.bin.tcpdump
# or reload everything:
#   sudo systemctl reload apparmor
#
# Inspect enforcement state any time with:
#   sudo aa-status
